Trump = "Word salad" Word salad is a "confused or unintelligible mixture of seemingly random words and phrases", most often used to describe a symptom of a neurological or mental disorder. The words may or may not be grammatically correct, but are semantically confused to the point that the listener cannot extract any meaning from them. The term is often used in psychiatry as well as in theoretical linguistics to describe a type of grammatical acceptability judgment by native speakers, and in computer programming to describe textual randomization.

Random observations from first presidential debate. ‚Ä¢ Trump started out very strong by focusing on jobs and economic policies. Once the moderator asked a question which had implications which might impugn his personality, however, and further lured from that point forward by Clinton with personal jabs, Trump reverted to his same old name-calling and buffoonery. He is, after all, or so he at least claims, a counter-puncher. His counter-punching did not serve him well. He had the initiative and he lost it. ‚Ä¢ Trump hammered on specific job and economic examples (e.g. an unfair tax differential between Mexico and the U.S., which actually impedes fair trade, to the detriment of the United States), Clinton responded with generalities and platitudes, and invoked the old "independent experts" mantra. I was so waiting for the famous Michael Gove comeback ("I think people in this country have had enough of experts"), but it was not to be. Trump missed his chance to obtain an early knockout blow on economic policy. Clinton was on the ropes, she was going to stand behind NAFTA, and he let her off the hook. NAFTA supporters consider free trade a system to be maximized. If you're a proper leader, you'd think of NAFTA as a mechanism by which the system of free trade could be optimized for the benefit of your country. In the latter case, NAFTA has failed miserably. ‚Ä¢ Trump, when pressed by Clinton on his business management practices, more-or-less 'fessed up to screwing over the suppliers, vendors, and contractors that he uses. Trump implied it was all OK, because he only "took advantage of the laws of the nation." The "rule of law" is not justice, and screwing over contractors is inflicting harm. Laborers and sole proprietor contractors don't have the wherewithal to challenge the likes of Trump in court for a ten thousand dollar contract dispute. So Trump screws over a hundred contractors for ten thousand dollars each, and it adds up. When injustice is done, and the system allows those who have perpetrated the injustice to get away with it (impunity), resentment against not only the wrongdoer, but the society at large ensues. We all pay the price for such improper behavior. First, we finance the legal system that enables such practices; and secondly, such practices sap the spirit of goodwill, efficiency, and fair dealing that are necessary for a coherent society, thus feeding the false narrative of zero-sum transactional economics. It's a crappy business practice (it's plain theft buttressed with intimidation under color of law); but hey, that's Trump. ‚Ä¢ In response to a question on race relations and "bridging the racial divide" (which, of course, presupposes that such a divide in fact exists), neither candidate addressed the question, and both quickly answered with criminal justice and enforcement plans ("law and order"). My goodness. Doesn't that just speak tons about how those candidates truly feel about race relations! The fact is, race relations are generally good, the minority communities are suffering the effect of the economic depression more so than the population as a whole, and the issue is therefore an economic issue. Crime is a separate issue. ‚Ä¢ Both candidates plan to spit on the Second Amendment by disallowing citizens that are on the so-called "terrorist watchlist" from obtaining weapons. This, of course, is hogwash, for not only does it fly in the face of the language of the Second Amendment itself ("the right ... shall not be infringed"), but the very purpose of the Second Amendment was to protect the citizenry from a government that runs amok. You can't very well then give to the government the right to create a secret watchlist (or any list for that matter) that prevents that right from being exercised! But this whole debate was a tour de force in muddled thinking. ‚Ä¢ Trump is all good with the idea that the priority mission of NATO should be re-purposed so as to combat terrorism. In fact, Trump would like to claim this new direction for NATO to be a result of his idea and prompting. This is not good news for those that believe the entire terrorist phenomenon is an intentionally constructed narrative to distract and deceive. Once Trump connects his self-esteem with an issue, rationality goes out the window. ‚Ä¢ Trump continued to seek to differentiate himself as not being a "professional politician," and repeatedly associated Clinton with a class of "political hacks" that have made poor economic and foreign policy decisions. Clinton invoked her panic button-like catch all "fact checker" squad. When confronted with the notion that her "experience," claimed to be related to poor policy decisions, was not something to be touted, Clinton sheepishly chose not to argue the case. It was a perfect opportunity for her to dive in to her accomplishments, but her silence surrendered the point. ‚Ä¢ I imagine each candidate gets to select some number of audience attendees. Trump keeps rolling out Don King, the boxing promoter. Professional boxing in the United States, since at least the 1920s, has been routinely fixed. I think the selection of King by Trump speaks volumes as to what Trump values. ‚Ä¢ Perhaps it was the stress of Clinton trying to land a last minute blow when the clock was ticking down, but the accusation that Trump believes "women don't deserve equal pay unless they do as good a job as a man" somehow left me with, "Well, yeah. So?" I guess the accusation might be that Trump thinks that it is conceivable that women in general are not capable of performing as well as men, but this is not what he said; and the real principle must be that the pay is based on the job, whatever that is, irrespective of the sex (or whatever other characteristic) of the worker. So I think Trump was trying to articulate the principle, and the over-reaching by Clinton came across as reaching for straws. ‚Ä¢ Trump cited a Clinton reference as springing from "the mainstream media." Just as Trump has done with free trade, for a major party presidential candidate to even utter those words in a nationally televised debate, in the totally controlled propaganda environment that is the United States, opens up the minds of millions of citizens, and gives them permission to even contemplate the notion of a national media dominated by "political hacks." ‚Ä¢ The prognostication by Trump during the primaries that he would "crush" Clinton in a one-on-one debate proved false. In fact, in terms of debate finesse, Clinton clearly had the better of Trump by luring him away from policy issues into personal areas where he felt challenged and responded immaturely. ‚Ä¢ In his closing remarks, Trump made a vague reference to some potential new accusation of Clinton scandal that, apparently, is so bad that even he, Donald Trump, felt it was in better taste to avoid mentioning. Then, of course, why did he mention it? It was a panic move, but maybe it appeals to soap opera fans. I don't know. Is this campaign a soap opera or a cartoon? ‚Ä¢ All in all it was a disappointing exhibition, with no knockout blow from either candidate, The good news is that neither candidate broke out of the cartoon character stereotype, so there's still a chance for a third party miracle!

This seems like a good year to be especially wary of the Bradley Effect, caused by respondents telling pollsters what the respondents think is the Okey-Dokey answer but doing something else on the Tuesday. This year it could actually work both directions, depending on where the respondents live--Clinton supporters living in Texas are in roughly same boat, mutatis mutandis, as Trump supporters living in Vermont. However, if it kicks in big nationwide, the polls are understating Trump's support in the popular nationwide vote.

As noted previously ( http://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/315003 ), there is growing evidence that the black community is far less united behind Clinton than some media commentators initially believed. Many community leaders are stepping back from full-throated endorsements of Clinton ("make up your own mind"), while others are even going so far as to support the ABC movement ("make up your own mind, so long as it's Anybody But Clinton"). A view from Australia (a land of odd politics itself). This is not a typical election - more uncertainty and risk with polar opinions, and (unlike Australia) without compulsory voting more hinges on who turns up on the day rather than just who likes whom. Moreover protest votes now have consequences (a Brexit style lesson which may not have reached America) and based on the Democrat convention the Clinton campaign appears to have moved into the sort of professionalism with grassroots vote gathering that should win swing states. Trump has surprised as a billionaire anti-establishment candidate, and could win if fear wild cards appear and they fall his way but he now looks less attractive as the reality of approaches of a president "outside normal parameters" even for P.J. O'Rourke confronts voters. Importantly- while most Australian's and our media may think Trump is a figure of fun - we don't vote and don't count. The lesson from the month long count for the final seat in our national election (won by 30 votes) is - all that couts is votes on the day in swing seats.

MARTIAL LAW: http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/martial_law.aspx "Martial law on the national level may be declared by Congress or the president. Under Article I, Section 8, Clause 15, of the Constitution, Congress has the power "[t]o provide for calling forth the Militia to execute the Laws of the Union, suppress insurrections and repel Invasions." Article II, Section 2, Clause 1, of the Constitution declares that "[t]he President shall be Commander in Chief of the Army and Navy of the United States, and of the Militia of the several States, when called into the actual Service of the United States." Neither constitutional provision includes a direct reference to martial law. However, the Supreme Court has interpreted both to allow the declaration of martial law by the president or Congress. On the state level, a governor may declare martial law within her or his own state. The power to do so usually is granted in the state constitution."

I've increased the odds in favor of a republican victory. Looking at past elections, a party that has held the presidency for 2 terms usually fails to keep it for a third. Starting with Ike, there have been a total of six presidential elections in which the same party held the white house for the previous two terms, and of those six, only one, Bush 1, managed to win a third term for his party. So 5/6=83% in favor of a republican. Since Bush v Gore was so close, I nudged it to 4.75/6=79% as my baseline. I'll admit starting with Ike is a bit arbitrary, but FDR's long run by no means happened in ordinary circumstances, and the further back we go, the more different the political landscape was.

I think Trump's winning of the Republican nomination is likely to trigger the entrance of one or more independent candidates into the race. Depending on who they are (e.g., Bloomberg), they will siphon off votes from the Republican ticket or both tickets. A stronger (more "moderate", better-connected) candidate like Bloomberg would draw off more Clinton votes. A weaker independent candidate (like any of the now side-lined Republicans) would affect Clinton less. Since I can't know who will enter the race, I'm forecasting an average effect of a race involving strong- and weak- 3rd party candidates. The percentages I predict roughly correspond to shares of the popular vote I would anticipate going to each party under those hypothetical scenarios.

To make this initial prediction, I am using the "mathematical models can help" method of CHAMPSKNOW. To start, I look at the polls for the general election which pit Trump versus the potential Democratic nominees, Clinton and Sanders. While these polls can sometimes be unreliable, I think there are a good starting point (potentially even a good "comparison class"), and given their consistency across one another, I think they work for the time being.

I find it difficult to give much weight to conventional political reasoning about Trump's appeal, viability, favorability ratings and the like. Strategically, Trump has upside potential from merely appearing reasonable during the general election campaign. He does not need to adopt the same aggressive tone with Clinton that he adopted in order to break out from the GOP primary pack; he may actively consider it a risk to do so (e.g., with women), which I think is accurate. The contrast between his "straight talk" and Clinton's will be, in my view, a strong theme for Trump. I think Clinton should have the edge on merit, but I think the consensus misjudges Trump's ability to reposition himself (as he has done with apparent electoral impunity on an almost weekly basis).

I broke the question down into four subcategories: Trump v. Clinton, Trump v. Sanders, Trump v. Clinton v. Independent and Trump v. Sanders v. Independent. (Independent here mostly meaning Michael Bloomberg but not exclusively). Clinton has to be seen as the heavy favourite to win the Democrat nod; Sanders is well back of the thresholds set out by 538 for him to win the nomination. I'd say it's 75-80% she wins. If she does, the likelihood of an independent bid is quite low, as it has been reported that Bloomberg is unlikely to enter the race unless it is a Sanders v. Trump bid. In a head-to-head match, Clinton's favourability ratings are far higher than Trump's and have been for some time and both are well-known figures within the general electorate so it seems valid to give Clinton a substantial lead; I'm guessing but I'd say this by a 2:1 margin. In the event of a Sanders victory, the situation becomes much less clear. Bloomberg's history of prevarication needs to be factored in, and another prominent independent candidate seems unlikely. Even in this case I'd say it's only 40% that Bloomberg even runs. Sanders is nowhere near as well known as Clinton, so favourability ratings may lie and the head-to-head polling at this point is rarely predictive. I don't know how to resolve this clash of unlikely candidates. I'm inclined to give Sanders a slight edge because Trump's favourability numbers are so bad and I'm also inclined to factor in a small chance of a win by Bloomberg or some other independent candidate in this scenario.
